  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Farewell to Liu Si'an
  author: Lee In-bok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    In this world, men are fuel that consumes itself in flame—
    Yet one of your brilliance deserves a place in history's page.
    You have steadied the realm in its hour of peril,
    And from level ground have become as immortal sage.

    The dreams of Five Lakes fade where green waters flow,
    In autumn's depth the wild chrysanthemums bloom fair.
    I am ashamed—I lack the courage to lay down my post and go,
    While snow now falls like frost upon my darkening hair.
  footnotes:
    - 'Five Lakes (五湖): A classical allusion to withdrawal from worldly affairs; reference to the Eastern Wu period or the legendary retreat of virtuous recluses.'
    - 'Three Paths (三徑): An allusion to Tao Yuanming''s famous retreat to a garden with three winding paths, symbolizing the hermit''s simple life and separation from official duties.'
    - The poem contrasts the addressee's noble withdrawal from service with the speaker's own inability to do the same, creating a poignant tension between admiration and self-reproach.
